What is a Network?
A network is a collection of devices (computers, phones, servers) connected together to share data and resources. Networks range from two laptops sharing files to the global Internet connecting billions of devices.

Core Network Components
1. Nodes / End Devices
These are the devices that send or receive data — desktops, laptops, smartphones, printers, servers. Every node has a unique MAC address (hardware level) and usually an IP address (logical level) to identify it on the network.
2. Network Interface Card (NIC)
Every device has a NIC — a hardware chip that lets it physically connect to a network. It can be wired (Ethernet port) or wireless (Wi-Fi). The NIC has a burned-in MAC address like 00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E.
3. Router
A router connects different networks together — most commonly your home network (LAN) to the Internet (WAN). It reads IP addresses and decides the best path to forward each packet. Routers also assign IP addresses via DHCP and perform NAT (Network Address Translation) so multiple devices share one public IP.
4. Switch
A switch connects devices within the same network (LAN). Unlike a hub (which blindly broadcasts to all ports), a switch is intelligent — it learns which MAC address is on which port and sends traffic only to the correct device. This makes LANs faster and more secure.
5. Hub (older technology)
A hub is the dumb predecessor to the switch. It broadcasts every packet to every connected device, letting the device itself decide if the packet is for it. This wastes bandwidth and is a security concern. Modern networks use switches instead.
6. Firewall
A firewall monitors and filters incoming and outgoing traffic based on rules. It can be hardware (a dedicated device) or software (like Windows Firewall). It blocks unauthorized access, malicious packets, and unwanted connections based on IP, port, and protocol rules.
7. Wireless Access Point (WAP)
A WAP transmits Wi-Fi signals so wireless devices can join the wired network. In homes, the router and WAP are usually combined into one box. In offices, multiple WAPs create coverage across large areas, all feeding into the main switch.
8. Modem
A modem (modulator-demodulator) converts digital signals from your computer into the analog signals that travel over telephone lines or cable, and converts them back. Your ISP provides this device. In modern setups, a modem-router combo handles both functions.
9. Server
A server is a device (or software) that provides services to other devices (clients). Types include web servers (host websites), file servers (share storage), DNS servers (translate domain names to IPs), DHCP servers (assign IP addresses), and mail servers.
10. Cables and Physical Media
The physical layer carries raw bits. Common types: Ethernet (Cat5e/Cat6) cables for wired LANs, fiber optic cables for high-speed long-distance links, and coaxial cables used by ISPs. Wireless (Wi-Fi, Bluetooth) uses radio waves instead.

Key Networking Concepts

IP Address — A logical address like 192.168.1.5 that identifies a device on a network. IPv4 uses 32-bit addresses; IPv6 uses 128-bit.

MAC Address — A hardware address burned into every NIC. Used within a local network to deliver frames.

DNS (Domain Name System) — Translates human-friendly names like google.com into IP addresses machines can route to.

DHCP — Automatically assigns IP addresses to devices joining a network, so you don't have to configure each one manually.

Protocol — A set of rules for communication. TCP/IP is the foundation of the Internet; HTTP handles web pages; FTP handles file transfers; SMTP handles email.

Bandwidth vs Latency — Bandwidth is how much data can flow per second (like a pipe's width). Latency is how long it takes a single packet to travel from source to destination (like the pipe's length).

LAN vs WAN — A Local Area Network (LAN) covers a building or campus. A Wide Area Network (WAN) spans cities or countries — the Internet is the world's largest WAN.




1. Network Fundamentals
A network is simply a group of devices (computers, phones, printers) connected together so they can share data. Think of it like roads connecting cities — the devices are cities, and the cables/Wi-Fi are the roads. Every network needs three things: devices to communicate, a physical link (cable or wireless), and protocols (rules so everyone "speaks the same language").

2. IP Address — Internet Protocol Address
Every device on a network gets a unique number called an IP address — just like every house has a unique postal address. Without it, data wouldn't know where to go.
There are two types: IPv4 looks like 192.168.1.10 (4 numbers, 0–255 each) and IPv6 looks like 2001:db8::1 (longer, for more devices). There are also public IPs (visible on the Internet) and private IPs (used only inside your home/office network).

3. DNS — Domain Name System
DNS is the Internet's phone book. Humans remember names like google.com, but computers need an IP address like 142.250.80.46. DNS automatically translates one to the other the moment you type a web address — so you never have to memorize numbers. Without DNS, you'd have to type the raw IP address into your browser every time.

4. DHCP — Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol
DHCP is the system that automatically gives every device an IP address when it connects to a network. Without DHCP, a network admin would have to manually assign an IP to every single device. With DHCP, it's automatic — your phone joins Wi-Fi, the router's DHCP server hands it an IP, and you're connected. Simple. 



The 5 key fundamentals explained simply

Packets — When you send data, it gets cut into small pieces called packets (like cutting a big letter into many postcards). Each packet travels independently and gets reassembled at the destination. This is why the Internet can carry millions of conversations at once.

Bandwidth — Think of it like a water pipe. A wider pipe moves more water per second. Higher bandwidth = more data per second. Measured in Mbps (megabits per second) or Gbps.

Latency — The delay between sending something and it arriving. Even at light speed, data from India to the USA takes ~80ms. Lower latency = faster feeling connections. This is why gaming servers are placed near players.

Client vs Server — Almost everything on the Internet works this way. You (the client) ask for something, the server provides it. Your browser is a client. Google's computers are servers. Servers run 24/7 waiting for requests.

Protocols — The agreed rules so all devices speak the same language. TCP/IP is the foundation of the Internet. HTTP is for web pages. SMTP is for email. Without protocols, a Windows PC and a Mac couldn't communicate at all.
